Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
Russia's invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the beginning of Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi appears to have given Putin a free hand to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and consider his confirmation as China's leader for life later in the year to be a mere formality.
After concentrating all power in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he would be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After obtaining Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his lifelong dream with incredible brutality.
At the approach of his 70s, Putin believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, it's now or never.
His conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar they can follow blindly.
It's precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it's a vision that distorts the "soul" of Russia, sentimental to the point of mushiness.
As a child, I encountered Russian soldiers many times when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I have learned that they are willing to share their last piece of bread with you if you ask them.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't know Putin personally, but I have observed his rise very closely, being aware of his cruelty.
He reduced the capital of Chechnya, Grozny, to nothing. And he threatens to do the same with the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB operator, but it seems he has changed lately.
Having developed a fixed idea, he appears to have lost touch with reality.
He certainly underestimated the situation in Ukraine.
He expected Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be on the same side as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Ukrainians have set up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that seems to be unstoppable.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are truly one people and that Ukrainians have been deceived by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But it was Putin who was misled in the second part.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 2014 Euromaidan protests.
The events of 2014 plunged him into black anger.
But the Russian army fared poorly when it received the order to attack its Ukrainian brethren.
Deep-seated corruption in the awarding of defense contracts also played a significant role in its poor results.
However, rather than beating himself up over it, Putin seems to have literally gone off the deep end.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and appears to be acting with no resistance at all.
He launches the entire Russian army into battle and ignores all the rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing the civilian population.
Many hospitals have been hit and the power grid feeding the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In the besieged Mariupol, 400,000 people went without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia may well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive arms to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MiG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
Whatever the outcome, Putin has already done wonders in managing to strengthen the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, it seems Xi has realized that Putin is acting alone.
On March 8, a day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi emphasized that the friendship between China and Russia remains "solid," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their efforts to restore peace.
He wanted to show maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It's far from certain that Putin will heed Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed before they destroy our civilization.
